WEBVTT

00:00:00.083 --> 00:00:02.583
Imagine if knowledge believed lost with the Library

00:00:02.595 --> 00:00:05.988
of Alexandria could be recovered—fragment by fragment,

00:00:06.238 --> 00:00:07.417
witness by witness.

00:00:07.810 --> 00:00:10.393
The web loses places more quietly, every day.

00:00:10.774 --> 00:00:13.786
Alexandria Here is a witnessed restoration engine for

00:00:13.798 --> 00:00:14.595
the lost web.

00:00:14.988 --> 00:00:16.464
Give it one public address.

00:00:16.845 --> 00:00:20.310
It inventories bounded Wayback evidence, finds a coherent

00:00:20.321 --> 00:00:23.940
surviving era, and returns a browsable place—without

00:00:23.952 --> 00:00:25.738
pretending the gaps were never there.

00:00:26.119 --> 00:00:29.833
This is iExile, founded by Jaia Papitz in 2007:

00:00:30.417 --> 00:00:33.250
a literary community returned from eight public captures

00:00:33.262 --> 00:00:35.619
spanning August through November 2009.

00:00:36.024 --> 00:00:36.976
Browse it normally.

00:00:37.357 --> 00:00:39.821
Then Show the Seams reveals the source, date,

00:00:40.060 --> 00:00:42.583
and content hash behind every returned block.

00:00:42.964 --> 00:00:45.857
Missing pages stay missing, with the surviving links

00:00:45.869 --> 00:00:47.262
that witness their absence.

00:00:47.643 --> 00:00:50.071
The Atlas makes the restoration challengeable.

00:00:50.452 --> 00:00:52.345
Timeline shows evidence windows.

00:00:52.726 --> 00:00:56.083
Witnesses exposes primary and alternate sources in groups

00:00:56.095 --> 00:00:56.940
of twenty-four.

00:00:57.321 --> 00:01:00.857
What Survived maps preserved rooms, inferred connections, and

00:01:00.869 --> 00:01:01.952
known absences.

00:01:02.345 --> 00:01:06.774
The receipt records 347 rendered blocks, 946

00:01:06.786 --> 00:01:09.905
source hashes, and ten of ten passing validations.

00:01:10.286 --> 00:01:12.643
Alexandria is not an iExile demo.

00:01:13.036 --> 00:01:15.631
The same public pipeline returned this historic Mars

00:01:15.643 --> 00:01:18.798
Pathfinder mission site from eight captures across February

00:01:18.810 --> 00:01:23.048
through April 1999: seven preserved pages, one missing

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:25.440
state, and twelve of twelve validations.

00:01:25.821 --> 00:01:28.655
Its 2001 window is inspected inside the same

00:01:28.667 --> 00:01:31.952
persisted recovery—no new archive query, no switched

00:01:31.964 --> 00:01:32.476
result.

00:01:32.857 --> 00:01:35.607
A missing path remains visible through cited surviving

00:01:35.619 --> 00:01:36.357
witnesses.

00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:39.619
GPT-5.6 is the Chronologist, not the

00:01:39.631 --> 00:01:40.345
historian.

00:01:40.738 --> 00:01:43.369
Deterministic code selects the evidence window.

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:47.167
GPT-5.6 orders the preserved pages and

00:01:47.179 --> 00:01:49.738
chooses one supplied primary witness for each.

00:01:50.119 --> 00:01:53.774
Deterministic validation then rejects every unknown identifier,

00:01:54.083 --> 00:01:56.595
unsupported citation, or altered hash.

00:01:56.976 --> 00:01:59.083
The model interprets evidence structure.

00:01:59.476 --> 00:02:01.548
It never writes historical content.

00:02:01.929 --> 00:02:05.190
Codex integrated the architecture, archive retrieval,

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:09.476
hostile-HTML handling, temporal reasoning, security, tests,

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:11.238
deployment, and browser audits.

00:02:11.631 --> 00:02:13.857
The result is a shipped public product, not

00:02:13.869 --> 00:02:14.893
a staged fixture.

00:02:15.274 --> 00:02:17.940
A recovery can also fail honestly when connected

00:02:17.952 --> 00:02:19.393
evidence is insufficient.

00:02:19.786 --> 00:02:22.167
Alexandria does not generate the past.

00:02:22.548 --> 00:02:24.643
It reconciles surviving witnesses.

00:02:25.036 --> 00:02:28.060
The lost web, present again—without pretending the

00:02:28.071 --> 00:02:29.238
gaps were never there.
